    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2>Marketing priorities for fashion stores</h2>
      <p>Fashion stores break when email treats every subscriber the same. The pressure point is seasonality, size availability, drops, and fast-moving inventory. A disciplined email marketing program must coordinate consent, lifecycle timing, product context, and margin-aware measurement — not blast more coupons.</p>
      <p>Priority plays: Drop and waitlist campaigns; Size and fit education; Back-in-stock by variant; Seasonal winback before clearance. Document suppressions for recent purchasers, wholesale accounts, and active support cases before scaling sends.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first for fashion stores because lifecycle editorial beats newsletter volume: welcome by signup source, replenishment matched to consumption, winback with VIP exclusions.</p>
      <p>Klaviyo remains the benchmark when fashion stores need predictive segmentation and native Shopify event depth at scale. Omnisend wins when email + SMS must go live before month end.</p>
      <p>Track Revenue per recipient by collection, Second purchase within 60 days, Return rate by email segment, Full-price vs discount purchase ratio weekly. Email ROI appears when incremental repeat purchase rises while unsubscribe and complaint rates stay flat.</p>
      <p>Buying cycle reality: 2–8 weeks between discovery and purchase; heavy browse behavior; high return rates on sizing. Email cadence must respect that rhythm — not the marketing calendar alone.</p>
      <p>Implementation: audit consent sources in week one, launch welcome segmented by source in week two, add cart or post-purchase in week three, measure repeat purchase movement in week four.</p>
      <p>Peak season for fashion stores requires pausing non-essential flows, protecting VIP segments, and aligning merchandising with inbox promises — governance matters more than new app installs.</p>
      <p>Deliverability note: fashion stores with aggressive promos need authentication, frequency caps, and sunset policies — complaint spikes often trace to offer mismatch, not weak templates.</p>
      <p>Pair capture tools (Privy, Justuno) only when list growth is the leak; pair Postscript when SMS recovery justifies cost. Avoid three senders without a collision calendar.</p>
      <p>Read comparisons and use-case playbooks on this site for head-to-head tradeoffs and execution detail specific to seasonality, size availability, drops, and fast-moving inventory.</p>
      <h3>Where fashion operators leak revenue</h3>
      <p>Size-related returns spike when post-purchase emails skip fit education. Drop hype trains one-time buyers when winback fires too early with deep discounts. Browse-heavy subscribers sit in cart recovery while full-price education would convert better. Shopify email marketing apps cannot fix merchandising — but they can stop sending stranger offers to recent full-price purchasers during clearance.</p>
      <p>Variant inventory sync is the technical gate. Back-in-stock and cart recovery that ignore size availability destroy trust faster than a weak subject line. Test Shopify webhook latency before scaling variant-triggered flows across peak drop season.</p>
      <p>Wholesale and marketplace channels need hard suppressions from DTC promo flows. Nothing erodes boutique positioning like a VIP early-access email followed by a marketplace discount notification — same brand, different channel, subscriber confusion.</p>
