      <h2>Extended email marketing playbook for fashion stores</h2>
      <p>This section is the retention magazine view of fashion stores: not which app has the prettiest templates, but which inbox moments actually move repeat purchase when seasonality, size availability, drops, and fast-moving inventory dominate operations.</p>
      <p>Start with consent archaeology. Map every popup, checkout, footer, SMS keyword, and partner import that feeds email. fashion stores often fail when giveaway subscribers receive the same welcome as high-intent product-page signups.</p>
      <p>Week-one deliverable: welcome segmented by source with suppressions for existing customers, recent purchasers, and employees. If your current tool cannot branch on signup source, that is the selection constraint — not missing AI copy features.</p>
      <p>Week-two deliverable: one recovery flow with inventory checks and discount caps documented. fashion stores lose margin when cart recovery treats a $35 accessory and a $350 bundle identically.</p>
      <p>Week-three deliverable: post-purchase education tied to 2–8 weeks between discovery and purchase; heavy browse behavior; high return rates on sizing. The email should reduce support tickets and set up the next purchase — not only ask for a review on day one.</p>
      <p>Week-four deliverable: replenishment or winback with VIP exclusions. Track Revenue per recipient by collection and Second purchase within 60 days against Shopify net sales, not only ESP attribution.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first in our fashion stores shortlist because agent-first playbooks compress those four weeks for lean teams. Klaviyo wins when someone owns predictive segments weekly. Omnisend wins when SMS must ship beside email immediately.</p>
      <p>Pricing discipline: model 90-day sends, not 90-day profiles. fashion stores with wide lists and narrow engagement punish per-contact billing — pay-per-email alternatives reward pruning and targeting.</p>
      <p>Sale-week governance: document which flows pause when site-wide promos run. Collision between welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and campaign blasts is the silent LTV killer for fashion stores.</p>
      <p>Deliverability preflight before peak season: SPF, DKIM, DMARC alignment, popup-offer match, sunset policies for 180-day inactives, and seedlist tests across Gmail and Apple Mail.</p>
      <p>When leaving a legacy sender, export consent timestamps and parallel-run critical flows two weeks. Attribution debates slow adoption more than template rebuilds.</p>
      <p>Final operator rule for fashion stores: email should feel like the store remembering the customer — product context, timing respect, and margin honesty. Pick the app your team will tune every Monday.</p>
      <p>Use the comparison hub when torn between two finalists — workflow tests beat feature matrices. Use use-case playbooks for trigger, timing, and exclusion detail on welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback.</p>
      <h3>Drop waitlist orchestration detail</h3>
      <p>Waitlist signup is high intent — treat it differently from footer subscribers. Confirmation email sets delivery expectation; VIP tier gets early access window with hard end time; public launch suppresses until VIP window closes. Sequenzy drop sequencing handles this logic when Shopify customer tags sync on waitlist join.</p>
      <p>Size-level waitlist matters for footwear and denim — "notify me" for US 9 is not the same as US 11 back-in-stock. Variant granularity separates professional fashion operators from generic DTC blasters using Shopify email marketing apps without catalog depth.</p>
      <h3>Seasonal clearance governance</h3>
      <p>Clearance email should exclude anyone who purchased full-price same category within 45 days. Seasonal winback before clearance targets lapsed buyers who missed the season — not recent full-price purchasers you are about to insult with 50%-off language.</p>
      <p>Document which collections enter clearance each week and align email segments to inventory age — not site-wide "everything must go" when only summer linen aged out. {segment.metrics[3]} tracks whether email trains discount dependency or protects margin.</p>
      <p>Peak season deliverability: authentication alignment, frequency caps during drop weeks, sunset 180-day inactives before Black Friday list imports. Fashion complaint spikes trace to offer mismatch — VIP early access recipient getting public sale blast — not template aesthetics.</p>
      <p>If you only fix one thing this quarter for fashion stores, fix suppression logic. Recent buyers, VIPs, wholesale accounts, and gift purchasers should not receive stranger-discount language — that single change often lifts placement and LTV more than a new template pack.</p>
      <p>Document Shopify email marketing apps ownership in a one-page runbook: Sequenzy lifecycle, Klaviyo segments, Privy capture, SMS layer — who pauses what during drop week. Revisit {segment.metrics.join(', ')} every Monday against Shopify net sales, not ESP attribution alone.</p>
