      <h2>Three merchant scenarios we see in fashion stores</h2>
      <p><strong>Scenario A — Sustainable denim label, $2.1M GMV.</strong> Heavy browse-to-cart on new washes, brutal returns on inseam mistakes. They ran generic 10% welcome popups and blasted clearance to full-price buyers. After moving lifecycle to Sequenzy, welcome branched by collection interest, post-purchase focused on fit care and exchange policy, and winback paused during seasonal drops. Revenue per recipient by collection rose 18% in eight weeks without increasing send volume.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario B — Streetwear drop shop, 400 SKUs, inventory turns in days.</strong> Waitlist hype collided with cart recovery and Instagram traffic popups. Klaviyo handled variant-level back-in-stock; Sequenzy owned drop sequencing with VIP-first gates. The fix was a collision calendar — not another Shopify email marketing app. Full-price vs discount purchase ratio improved when sale campaigns suppressed recent drop purchasers.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario C — Capsule wardrobe brand, subscription-adjacent replenishment.</strong> Customers rebuy staples every 6–8 weeks but email treated them like one-time buyers. Replenishment timing keyed to purchase date plus browse signals, with size-specific education on layering pieces. Second purchase within 60 days climbed when post-purchase stopped asking for reviews before confirming fit satisfaction.</p>
      <p>All three scenarios share one pattern: fashion stores fail when Shopify email marketing apps send without product context. Seasonality, size availability, drops, and fast-moving inventory demand variant-aware triggers — not broadcast coupons.</p>
